#mimijung #미미정

Early this year, I changed the marking on my crates to include my last name in Korean, “정.” 

The addition was to remind those who receive it to once again consider me and my work holistically.

The timing of the change was kismet as I returned to Seoul, my birthplace, just this month after six years of putting it off. Some Korean Americans will relate to my reluctance. Growing up in the States, I’m constantly reminded of my “otherness” only to return to Korea, where I can feel alienated for being “Americanized.” 

During my childhood, I was oblivious to it. In my young adulthood, I felt the separation deeply, and now, I feel my limbo state of identity finally recognized, or it may just be that I feel more settled in my skin.

On this recent trip (see saved stories 🛩️🇰🇷), I felt my love for Korea take deeper roots. I made new friends, renewed old bonds, and found nooks in all neighborhoods that fit like a glove.

I am once again committed to finding more opportunities to go back home for more 🤍🇰🇷

#mimijung #미미정

My objective was to utilize a spectrum of blue hues in the warp, weft, and painted panel, such that when interwoven, they undergo alterations in response to fluctuations in ambient light conditions. A singular photograph fails to adequately capture the dynamism of this combination. Therefore, a time-lapse video documents the evolving interplay of color and dimension over the course of a day. 
☀️⏳🌙
